segments.text: You know, that that was not my strong suit, but I had, I think I've always exhibited common sense and some leadership ability apparently, and they gave me credit for what I had and did not diminish me for what I did not have.
During your student era,
Describe generally the attitudes of the typical Aggie student.
Were they rich, poor, conservative, liberal, what?
Conservative and poor.
There were a handful of guys that had cars, so you thought they were rich.
Just to have a car, you had to be rich.
And where did they come from geographically?
Everywhere.
And in today's politically correct definition of diversity, how diverse was the student body?
It wasn't.
It wasn't.
I remember quite a few Hispanics, like I described earlier.
I know drill team.
We had an enormous number of guys from Central Catholic High School.
And how were those Hispanics treated?
Just like, I think everybody was treated just exactly the same.
I don't think there was a bit of difference.
To my knowledge, there was no difference while I was a student.
Were there any, well, by the time you graduated, there were some black students.
There were a handful.
I didn't personally know any.
I knew them, you know, just I knew some names of two or three of them, but I didn't really know any of them.
All right.
How does that relate to whatever Aggie spirit is?
What is Aggie spirit?
The impact is that I think you end up with knowing individuals, be they student friends that become lifelong members or

the even if it is two or three faculty or staff that you remember, the impact of silver taps and muster and a few ceremonies, and the fact that you had an experience that just molds you to be prepared to do whatever you decide you want to do.
And that ends up equaling a spirit.
And then you learn right away that the former students that are out there are going to accept you immediately.
It doesn't matter if it says double ought or 65.
The number on the ring is immaterial to everybody that has one.
Does the person's academic major matter?
Not to the spirit.
It doesn't matter.
You've got 25 years now.

You've got to give different answers for the last 20 years, and especially the last 10 years, because the quality of the guy that had a diploma from high school has long ago not been able to get in here.
But you still have these high-quality young people that want to be touched
by the spirit and the Aggie connection and the friendships and see all of that when they're coming in the door and want to be impacted by it immediately.
The stories of these 12 kids that lost their lives this year, absolutely awesome young people to where it reminds you that that's what all of them are.
It wasn't just accidentally that 12.
That is the example.
They are all like that.
An enormous number of them are valedictorians.
An enormous number of those guys were all Eagle Scouts.
They did try to help people while they were up there on that stack and point at somebody else.
I mean, just awesome young people that
Through this period of time, what they're going to do in the next 50 years is anything they want to go do.
And the leadership examples that will be available 40 years from now compared to the leadership examples that are available now will be off the books.
Now, in your day, not many students went to fish camp, did they?
No, it was summer school at Junction.
Yeah, yeah.
It had the same role.
It was limited for that reason.
I couldn't afford to go that summer or I would have probably gone.
It would have been good for me if I could have gone.
Because I today think that part of the Aggie spirit.
We have 4,000 freshmen of 6,300 that go through fish camp.
And so they get connected immediately.
Yep, yep.
You have 11,000 kids live on campus out of the 36,000 undergraduates.
It's huge.
The residential living is a huge part of feeling connected and knowing people and the involvement level.
And I'll bring back another day for just a five or ten minute visit.
I've got some data gathered.
If you measure the quality of the student body by the percentage of all undergraduates who were in the top ten percent of their high school class,
This is the best student body in the Big 12.
Tech, Kansas State, and Nebraska are at the bottom.
Texas is second.

When I mention this to anybody, I try to always indicate one of the great blessings Texas A&M has is to have another top-notch public school 100 miles away, and everything they achieve, we want to outdo and vice versa, ratchet each other up.
that we have a comparatively, compared to most schools, have a comparatively high percentage living on campus.
We're eighth in the country on campus living.
We have about 91% of the students went to high school in Texas, but the diversity geographically is increasing and that's healthy.
And the great problem of the future is how many students to enroll and how do you select them?
Do you get more and more and more?
That's a difficult one.
I'm the only guy that would like to go to 55,000 because you do not change the quality of the kids coming in by going to 55,000.
No.
Because the 4,000 turned down this year were fully qualified.
And by expectation would be doing just as well as anybody as the ones that were admitted.
The limitation is resources, space, faculty, time.
Let's see.
Only two or three things left.
What do you think it meant to you that you attended Texas A&M?

For my background coming from the family that I did and having the chance to get a college education and then have a, at least at that moment, a very clear direction of military service put me off on a road that gave me a chance to change my mind later.
What did you learn at Texas A&M, defining the word learn now in its broadest?
I think that I had reinforced family values of integrity.
I think I learned integrity.
I learned common sense, hard work, the right way to do something.
began to learn the importance of friendships and how to nurture them and make them work and appreciate them.
I've had a chance to give back to a degree greater than almost anybody has.
But I'm very grateful that I've had that chance because I wouldn't have mounted to a hill of beans.
All right.
The next to last one.
Let's make believe somebody walked up to you when the lottery is finished tonight and handed you a million-dollar check with only one condition.
You must pass it on to A&M, but you can decide what use to be made of it.
What would you?
It would be the Malin Sutherland Quality of Student Life Endowment.
where the Vice President for Student Affairs can decide what student needs $500 to go to England or $500 to pay the rent or whatever good purpose, educational or need-based.
I've run into many, many old-timers
who say that the opportunity award which their FFA or their advisor helped them to get literally changed their life.
Last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M?
We don't have enough time.
You'll have to bring another tape.
The quality of the people that I have known and

been touched by and maybe had the ability to touch to some degree is enormous and is not the experience that most human beings get to have in the full power of a relationship from knowing an 18-year-old freshman to knowing them as a four-star general.
and the enormous change that happens and that you can see and see what the ability to have some success in an environment at A&M really prepares you dramatically well for the real world.
Let's quit there.
